Think_Book: I like that they're "green"--no trees have to die to publish digital books. I also like that they're interactive. I think books like R.L. Stine's _Goosebumps_ series "Reader Beware: You Choose the Scare," where readers choose what the main character will do next and flip through the book to find the next page rather than reading it sequentially, are perfect for this medium. Reference books, travel books, and children's picture books are also easily expressed in digital format. Lastly, games could also be produced in digital form--crossword puzzles, word searches, sudoku, et al. In addition, since there is virtually no overhead (discounting formatting, of course), novelists could self-publish very easily.
Think_Stud: It was interesting and informative. Australia was just exotic enough to keep my attention, yet familiar enough not to freak me out with its weirdness. I would have rather seen Ireland, though, because along with the exotic/familiar aspect, its castles lend an air of mysticism and magic. Also, the perpetual green would subliminally remind the reader of the "green" aspect of digital books, and hence, provide the opportunity to address that aspect in the survey.

Think_Book: The book excerpt was really dense and so many things going on in the left hand panel. I can understand that the digital book wanted tips and little blurbs about what places are a must see, but it looked more like a review from other people. There weren't a lot of pictures that showed what Australia looks like. It's more text if anything. I mean I know it's a book, but it was so boring and uninteresting that I quickly tired of it. The fact that the opening bit wasn't that enticing to me to begin with, I quickly lost interest. It's supposed to be a travel book, make the would-be tourist engaged and want to visit Australia, don't bore them to tears and wonder why they bought such an awful book. This book looked more like a study for someone trying to do a boring book report. It doesn't make the average person who wants to tour Australia want to go there. It may have had lots of information, they just set it up in a way that didn't seem all that inviting.

Think_Book: I thought the digital book was very interactive and did well to integrate the pictures with the text. For example, when the text described a particular place in Australia I could simply hover my cursor over the name of the place and a picture would appear of that place enhancing the description from the text. This integration improved my understanding of the text and enhanced its credibility. As to digital books in general, I think they are an effective tool to integrate pictures and text more effectively than print books and have far more convenient and intuitive tools. For example, I have e-reading software on my computer and I've bought a couple of digital books from Amazon. While I was reading one of them I came across a word I didn't know. All I had to do was right click on the word and the definition for it appeared making it far easier to learn the word and understand the text as opposed to being forced to pull out a dictionary and flip through the pages to find the definition or open up my web browser and search an online dictionary. In this respect I think e-books are more effective than print books. In addition, the cost of e-books should be significantly lower than print books due to the fact the book no longer has to be type-set, run through a printer, stored in warehouses, and then finally shipped to customers. It is for that reason that I won't pay much more than $4 for an e-book in general.
